<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>POWER STEERING GEAR: SHEPPARD M-SERIES - STEERING GEAR DISASSEMBLE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="28">
        <title>STEERING GEAR DISASSEMBLE</title>
        <para>The diagnosis and troubleshooting section of this manual has been prepared to help with proper diagnosis.
            Repair time and downtime as well as repair costs can be reduced if needless disassembly and replacement of
            steering gear parts are avoided. Before removing the steering gear from the chassis, you must be certain
            that the hydraulic supply system is operating properly and that all mechanical components are in good
            repair.
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <important>
                <para>The Sheppard integral power steering gear is a precision machined assembly and care must be taken
                    during repair to keep it free of dirt and foreign material. All internal parts must be handled
                    carefully to avoid damages to machined surfaces. Nicks or burrs can cause damage to mating parts and
                    must be removed with a fine hand stone before reassembly. Working on a soft cardboard or plywood
                    surfaced workbench is best. Follow disassembly procedures as required.
                </para>
            </important>
        </specpara>
        <para>Remove the tab lock retainer and pitman arm. Refer to the
            <hotlnk document="s05015y_X0501515.xml" xrefid="x0501515">PITMAN ARM, REMOVE</hotlnk>.
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the rubber sector shaft boot (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501561">Figure 61</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501561" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500246.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 61. Remove Rubber Sector Shaft Boot</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the mounting bracket bolts and separate the mounting bracket from the steering gear
                (if equipped) (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501562">Figure 62</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501562" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500247.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 62. Remove Mounting Bracket Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the dirt shield from the end of the sector shaft with an Allen wrench (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501563">Figure 63</hotlnk>). Later model steering gears will use a stick-on dirt
                shield which can be removed using a stiff putty knife.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501563" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500248.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 63. Remove Dirt Shield</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a center punch to make two reference marks on the bearing cap and corresponding marks on
                the housing. A single reference mark should be made on the cylinder head and a corresponding mark on the
                housing, so the gear can be reassembled in the same configuration (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501564">Figure 64</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501564" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500249.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 64. Make Reference Marks</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Wear safety glasses; sharp metal from the punch or housing can injure an eye.</para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the relief valve plungers from both ends of the gear. This will protect them from
                damage during repair (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501565">Figure 65</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501565" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500250.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 65. Remove Relief Valve Plungers</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the bolts attaching the sector shaft cover to the housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501566">Figure 66</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501566" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500251.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 66. Remove Sector Shaft Cover Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a soft hammer to tap on the end of the sector shaft to loosen the cover (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501567">Figure 67</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501567" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500252.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 67. Loosen Cover</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Carefully slide the sector shaft and cover out of the housing. Slide the cover off the
                sector shaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501568">Figure 68</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501568" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500253.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 68. Slide Sector Shaft and Cover Out of Housing</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard the cover O-ring and sector shaft seal (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501569">Figure 69</hotlnk>) or the 3-piece seal assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501570">Figure 70</hotlnk>) (if equipped).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501569" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500254.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 69. Remove Cover O-Ring and Sector Shaft Seal</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0501570" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500255.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 70. Remove 3-Piece Seal Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the cylinder head and discard both the seal ring and the tetra seal (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501571">Figure 71</hotlnk>
                and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501572">Figure 72</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501571" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500256.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 71. Remove Cylinder Head</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0501572" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500257.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 72. Discard Seal Ring and Tetra Seal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the face seal from the input shaft (if equipped) (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501573">Figure 73</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501573" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500258.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 73. Remove Face Seal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the attaching bolts from the bearing cap and turn the input shaft to free the bearing
                cap assembly from the housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501574">Figure 74</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501574" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500259.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 74. Remove Bearing Cap Attaching Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>After the bearing cap assembly is free from the housing, keep the shaft stationary. Binding of
                        the shaft and shaft damage may occur if the shaft is removed at this time (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0501574">Figure 74</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Carefully slide the piston and bearing cap assembly from the housing bore until the ball
                guide retainer is located (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501575">Figure 75</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501575" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500260.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 75. Slide Piston and Bearing Cap Assembly From Housing Bore</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>The ball guide retainer must be held in place. If not, the ball return guides and steel balls
                        will drop out of the assembly. Loss of the steel balls may occur (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0501576">Figure 76</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0501576" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500261.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 76. Hold Ball Guide Retainer in Place</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Screw a small sheet metal screw into the ball guide retainer until 2 to 3 threads are
                engaged. Use a pair of pliers to remove the ball guide retainer from the piston (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501577">Figure 77</hotlnk>
                and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501578">Figure 78</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501577" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500262.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 77. Remove Ball Guide Retainer</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0501578" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500263.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 78. Remove Ball Guide Retainer</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Piston Variation</emph>
                - Some steering gears are equipped with a bolt on ball guide retainer. Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501579">Figure 79</hotlnk>,
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501580">Figure 80</hotlnk>
                and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501581">Figure 81</hotlnk>
                for disassembly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501579" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500264.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 79. Bolt On Ball Guide Retainer Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0501580" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500265.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 80. Bolt On Ball Guide Retainer Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0501581" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500266.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 81. Bolt On Ball Guide Retainer Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>With bolt on retainers, remove the mounting bolts and ball guide retainer. Remove and discard
                        the seal ring from the retainer (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0501580">Figure 80</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Do not remove the piston at this time. Leave the piston in the housing with the ball guide
                exposed (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501581">Figure 81</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the ball return guides. The steel balls are then free to roll out of the ball cavity
                in the piston (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501582">Figure 82</hotlnk>
                and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501583">Figure 83</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501582" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500267.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 82. Remove Ball Return Guides</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0501583" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500268.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 83. Remove Steel Balls</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>It will be necessary to rotate the shaft in and out slightly to remove all the steel balls. 24
                        steel balls are contained in the piston and must be removed before the input shaft and bearing
                        cap assembly removal can be completed.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">After removal of the 24 balls, the input shaft and bearing cap assembly may be removed from
                the piston. At this time the seal ring and tetra seal may be removed and discarded (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501584">Figure 84</hotlnk>
                and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501585">Figure 85</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501584" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500269.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 84. Remove Input Shaft and Bearing Cap Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0501585" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500270.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 85. Remove Seal Ring and Tetra Seal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Carefully slide the piston from the housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501586">Figure 86</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501586" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500271.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 86. Slide Piston From Housing</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard the sector shaft seal from the housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501587">Figure 87</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501587" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500272.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 87. Discard Sector Shaft Seal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The steering gear is now disassembled. Necessary parts may be replaced as needed (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0501588">Figure 88</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0501588" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/g0500273.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 88. Steering Gear Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
